Question: How do you believe ACME should better support organizations and cultural leaders?

Response ID: resp_332
Response Text: As a manager of a small "legacy" organization, I can attest that we provide employment for 100-200 independent contractors annually. By not guaranteeing us stable funding, we cannot continue to produce a full program and must continue to shrink. This reduces employment opportunities for artists, technicians, designers, etc., who must go elsewhere to make a living--or leave the profession altogether.  And the lack of performance and rehearsal facilities is criminal. In the last two years, the cost of doing business for us has increased approximately 30%. Much of that is facility costs. With all of the empty commercial real estate in the city, I don't understand why some of it can't be converted into performance spaces. Leadership from the former arts-related offices within the city of Austin and the arts community is lacking. We now have a fractured arts community where everyone is pitched against everyone else. We need to stop this and start bringing people together. And please, can we stop making  "art" and "quality" dirty words? What we don't need is more training, or to be displaced by new arrivals with no connection to the city and no meaningful experience in the profession.

